AWS S3 Static Website Hosting Documentation

Task Assigned by Mentor

Task Objective:
Upload an HTML file into an Amazon S3 bucket, configure static website hosting, make the website publicly accessible, and verify successful hosting through the S3 website endpoint.

---

Project Objective

The objective of this task was to understand how Amazon S3 can be used for static website hosting by uploading an HTML file, configuring public access permissions, enabling website hosting, and verifying hosted website accessibility through a browser.

This task also helped in understanding cloud-based website hosting without managing a server.

---

Services and Technologies Used

• Amazon S3
• HTML
• AWS Management Console
• Static Website Hosting
• Bucket Policy (JSON)

---

Project Workflow

HTML File Creation
↓
Amazon S3 Bucket Creation
↓
Upload HTML File to Bucket
↓
Enable Static Website Hosting
↓
Configure Public Access Permission
↓
Generate Website Endpoint
↓
Verify Website Hosting in Browser

---

STEP 1: Understanding the Task Requirement

Task Understanding:

The mentor assigned the task to host an HTML webpage inside Amazon S3 and make it publicly accessible.

Before implementation, the following understanding was developed:

• HTML file would act as webpage content
• Amazon S3 bucket would store website files
• Static Website Hosting would allow S3 to behave like a website host
• Bucket permissions would make the website publicly accessible
• Website endpoint would be used to open the hosted webpage

Learning:

Understood that Amazon S3 can host static websites without requiring a traditional web server.

---

STEP 2: HTML File Creation

Implementation:

Initially, confusion occurred regarding creation of an HTML file because a text editor such as Notepad was not readily used.

Questions/Confusion Faced:
• How to create an HTML file?
• Which software should be used?
• How to save the file in .html format?
• Difference between .txt and .html extension?

Resolution:

Instead of Notepad, an available editor option was explored and a text-based file was created.

A simple webpage structure was written using HTML.

Example webpage content included:

• Website title
• Heading text
• Paragraph text

File name created:

index.html

Verification Performed:

The file extension was verified to ensure that the created file was:

.html

and not:

.txt

Reason for Verification:

A .txt file would not work as a webpage during hosting.

Learning:

HTML files are used to create webpage content and browsers render .html files as websites.

---

STEP 3: Amazon S3 Bucket Creation

Implementation:

1. Logged into AWS Console.
2. Opened Amazon S3 service.
3. Clicked “Create Bucket”.
4. Entered unique bucket name.
5. Selected default configuration.
6. Created bucket successfully.

Understanding:

An Amazon S3 bucket works as cloud storage where files are stored.

Simple Understanding:

Bucket = Cloud Folder

Purpose:

The bucket would store website files for hosting.

Learning:

Amazon S3 stores files such as:
• HTML
• Images
• CSS
• Documents
• Videos

---

STEP 4: Public Access Configuration

Implementation:

During bucket configuration, “Block Public Access” settings were reviewed.

Action Performed:

Disabled:

“Block all public access”

Acknowledgment confirmation was accepted.

Question Faced:

Why disable public access?

Understanding Developed:

By default, Amazon S3 keeps files private.

Since website hosting required public accessibility, users needed permission to open website files through a browser.

Purpose:

Without public access:

Website would show:

Access Denied

Learning:

Public access permissions are required when hosting public websites on Amazon S3.

---

STEP 5: Uploading HTML File to S3 Bucket

Implementation:

1. Opened created bucket.
2. Selected Upload option.
3. Added index.html file.
4. Uploaded file successfully.
5. Verified uploaded file.

Understanding:

The uploaded HTML file became website content stored inside AWS cloud storage.

Purpose:

S3 bucket stores webpage files which are later served as website content.

Learning:

Website files must be uploaded before enabling hosting.

---

STEP 6: Enabling Static Website Hosting

Implementation:

1. Opened bucket Properties section.
2. Scrolled to Static Website Hosting.
3. Clicked Edit.
4. Enabled Static Website Hosting.
5. Selected:

“Host a static website”

6. Added:

index.html

as index document.

7. Saved changes.

Question Faced:

What is index.html?

Understanding Developed:

index.html acts as the homepage of a website.

When website URL opens, AWS automatically loads:

index.html

Purpose:

Convert Amazon S3 bucket into a website hosting service.

Learning:

Static Website Hosting allows S3 bucket files to be served as webpages.

---

STEP 7: Bucket Policy Configuration

Implementation:

1. Opened Permissions section.
2. Navigated to Bucket Policy.
3. Added JSON policy.
4. Allowed:

s3:GetObject

permission.

Question Faced:

Why add bucket policy?

Understanding Developed:

Even after public access configuration, browser access still requires read permission.

Bucket policy grants permission to public users to open website files.

Purpose:

Allow browser users to read files stored inside bucket.

Without Bucket Policy:

Access Denied

Learning:

Bucket policies manage access permissions in Amazon S3.

---

STEP 8: Website Endpoint Verification

Implementation:

1. Opened bucket Properties.
2. Copied website endpoint URL.
3. Opened endpoint in browser.
4. Verified website loaded successfully.

Result:

Hosted webpage opened successfully through browser.

Understanding:

The endpoint acts as website URL generated by Amazon S3.

Learning:

Website endpoint provides public access to hosted website files.

